column15: President Macron has announced the reopening of nurseries, schools, and colleges in metropolitan France and overseas, starting on June 22nd. In schools and colleges, physical distance regulations have been eased. Instead of the required 4m2 per pupil, a one-metre distance must be observed between the teacher and pupils (and between pupils themselves) in classrooms and confined spaces. https://web.archive.org/web/20200713070356/https://www.vie-publique.fr/discours/274578-emmanuel-macron-14062020-covid-19
column18: On 22nd June, the next phase of deconfiment was entered, with the whole of France being declared a "green zone" with little to no workplace closures (except for discotheques and fair grounds). Advice is as following: Working from home must be preferred whenever possible. If you cannot work from home, staggered work patterns must be encouraged, to reduce the numbers of people both in the workplace and in public transport. Therefore, downgraded to 1G; https://web.archive.org/web/20200715180019/https://www.gouvernement.fr/en/coronavirus-covid-19 https://web.archive.org/web/20200629224753/https://www.aa.com.tr/en/europe/macron-details-phase-3-of-deconfinement-in-france/1876966
column27: True return to normal for almost all public transport in Paris and Ile-de-France. All metro stations will be open from June 22, 2020. Almost all RATP buses, tram, metro and RER are working at 100%. The same goes for the majority of Transilien SNCFs. https://web.archive.org/web/20200722155345/https://www.francebleu.fr/infos/transports/transports-en-commun-en-ile-de-france-toutes-les-stations-de-metro-seront-ouvertes-a-partir-du-22-1592483057
column30: From June 22, the French government communicates that movements inside cities, between regions, in public transports etc. are allowed. There is no mention of 'staying at home'. https://web.archive.org/web/20200915102027/https://twitter.com/gouvernementFR/status/1276526016803020804/photo/1
column33: Although travel to French overseas territories is more difficult and restricted, travel within metropolitan France is permitted and citizens may travel freely yet responsibly. Masks must be worn at all times. https://web.archive.org/web/20200701055822/https://www.gouvernement.fr/en/coronavirus-covid-19

column35: The Schengen space is open to a restricted number of countries since July 1. The list is updated every 2 weeks in accordance to the evolution of the situation in each country. https://web.archive.org/web/20200916142106/https://www.cnewyork.net/2020/07/31/liste-des-pays-autorises-union-europeenne-aout-2020/

The official EU webpage says the following about quarantine: "No compulsory quarantine for travellers from EU, Schengen area and UK. Quarantine when travelling to overseas and voluntary quarantine for travellers from the UK. Symptomatic travellers during border health checks should be subject to quarantine, regardless of their nationality." https://web.archive.org/web/20200706170147/https://reopen.europa.eu/en/map/FRA

column21: Stadiums and racing tracks may reopen to the public from 11 July. There is an upper limit of 5,000 people per venue. https://web.archive.org/web/20200927114257/https://www.gouvernement.fr/en/coronavirus-covid-19 However, at the request of the Council of State which had been seized, demonstrations subject to the obligation of a prior declaration are again authorized. The participants must not be more than 5,000 and must respect the sanitary rules (physical distance of at least one meter between people, systematic wearing of the mask when the respect of this distance is not guaranteed, barrier gestures). https://web.archive.org/web/20200916095459/https://www.service-public.fr/particuliers/actualites/A14105

In most cities, the 14th of July's festivities were cancelled. Gatherings of more than 5000 are forbidden, but firework shows were still on in some cities, in various locations to avoid the formation of crowds. https://web.archive.org/web/20200915143427/https://france3-regions.francetvinfo.fr/hauts-de-france/carte-14-juillet-covid-19-voici-feux-artifice-concerts-maintenus-nord-pas-calais-1852168.html

column58: Since 20 July, it is compulsory for all people aged 11 and over to wear face masks in enclosed public spaces. Some local authorities (including Paris) have extended this to outdoor public spaces as well. There is a fine for not complying with these restrictions. Since 11 May, it has been compulsory to wear masks on public transport, taxis, and private hire vehicles that do not have a plexiglass screen. Fines also apply for non-compliance. https://web.archive.org/web/20200831205158/https://www.gov.uk/foreign-travel-advice/france/coronavirus

column49: Tests are free and can be carried out without a medical prescription and on non-symptomatic patients since July 25, 2020. https://web.archive.org/web/20200915140317/https://twitter.com/MinSoliSante/status/1297149019739873280?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1297149019739873280%7Ctwgr%5Eshare_3&ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linternaute.fr%2Factualite%2Fguide-vie-quotidienne%2F2489431-test-covid-19-publics-prioritaires-tentes-de-depistage-ce-qui-va-changer%2F "Afin de faciliter le d矇pistage de la Covid-19, les tests PCR sont totalement pris en charge par l'assurance maladie et ne n矇cessitent pas de prescription d'un m矇decin". https://web.archive.org/web/20200915135127/https://www.gouvernement.fr/info-coronavirus/tests-et-depistage https://web.archive.org/web/20200915135513/https://solidarites-sante.gouv.fr/soins-et-maladies/maladies/maladies-infectieuses/coronavirus/tout-savoir-sur-la-covid-19/article/se-faire-depister-lieux-et-conditions

column35: Travellers from authorised countries outside the EU must provide a negative PCR test, or undergo a test at the airport, or quarantine themselves for 2 weeks. https://web.archive.org/web/20200916140946/https://www.gouvernement.fr/info-coronavirus/vacances

column58: Masks are still mandatory in all closed spaces https://web.archive.org/web/20200915092101/https://www.gouvernement.fr/info-coronavirus/masques-grand-public and, from August 3, pr矇fets can decide to make it mandatory at all times outside the home locally: https://web.archive.org/web/20200915134412/https://twitter.com/JeanCASTEX/status/1290210634722729984?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1290210634722729984%7Ctwgr%5Eshare_3&ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.france24.com%2Ffr%2F20200804-quelles-sont-les-villes-de-france-oC3B9-le-masque-est-obligatoire-en-extC3A9rieur This measure has been implemented in various cities. https://web.archive.org/web/20200915092204/https://www.leparisien.fr/societe/la-carte-des-communes-qui-imposent-le-port-du-masque-en-exterieur-02-08-2020-8362416.php

column18: Nothing has changed with this policy. https://web.archive.org/web/20200701055822/https://www.gouvernement.fr/en/coronavirus-covid-19
column27: Nothing has changed with this policy. https://web.archive.org/web/20200701055822/https://www.gouvernement.fr/en/coronavirus-covid-19
column33: Nothing has changed with this policy. https://web.archive.org/web/20200701055822/https://www.gouvernement.fr/en/coronavirus-covid-19

column18: Since August 14, several departments (i.e. counties) have 'turned to red', which means that local authorities can decide on restricting activities or closing certain businesses (bars, theatres, pools, markets...). The main departments effected are: The North, the Bas-Rhin, the Seine-Maritime, the C繫te-d'Or , the metropolis of Lille, Rouen, Le Havre, Strasbourg, Dijon - the two departments of Corsica (Corsica- du-Sud and Haute-Corse) and Reunion Island. https://web.archive.org/web/20200915142813/https://www.rtbf.be/info/societe/detail_france-sept-nouveaux-departements-classes-en-zone-de-circulation-active-du-coronavirus?id=10577551 https://web.archive.org/web/20200915082254/https://www.bfmtv.com/sante/covid-19-quelles-mesures-les-prefets-peuvent-ils-prendre-dans-les-zones-rouges_AV-202009130122.html https://web.archive.org/web/20200915085810/https://www.gouvernement.fr/info-coronavirus/loisirs Remote work is no longer "the norm" but simply recommended: "Le t矇l矇travail nest plus la norme mais peut rester une solution privil矇gier en cas de circulation active du virus." https://web.archive.org/web/20200915082351/https://www.gouvernement.fr/info-coronavirus/retour-au-travail Night clubs have not been allowed to open throughout the period closed.

column35: Ban on certain countries maintained, with exceptions. https://web.archive.org/web/20200916144926/https://www.diplomatie.gouv.fr/en/coming-to-france/coronavirus-advice-for-foreign-nationals-in-france/

The policy has not significantly evolved, the list of non EU countries authorised is updated regularly in consultation with EU members. /web/20200916143049/https://www.diplomatie.gouv.fr/fr/le-ministere-et-son-reseau/actualites-du-ministere/informations-coronavirus-covid-19/coronavirus-les-reponses-a-vos-questions/article/coronavirus-les-reponses-a-vos-questions

column15: All students and professors who return to school on Tuesday, 1st September will have to wear masks. If a student displays symptoms, a protocol on dealing with this will be in place. https://web.archive.org/web/20200827221555/https://www.gouvernement.fr/sites/default/files/document/document/2020/08/presentation_-_point_de_situation_sur_la_covid-19_-_27.08.2020.pdf

column21: The Tour de France started on August 29. https://web.archive.org/web/20200915143200/https://www.lemonde.fr/sport/article/2020/04/15/le-cyclisme-se-raccroche-a-un-tour-decale-fin-aout-pour-assurer-sa-survie_6036621_3242.html

column24: In red zones, pr矇fets can forbid gatherings of 10 or more. The department of Bordeaux has lowered the 5000-person limit for public gatherings (that are applied nationwide) down to 1000. https://web.archive.org/web/20200915082254/https://www.bfmtv.com/sante/covid-19-quelles-mesures-les-prefets-peuvent-ils-prendre-dans-les-zones-rouges_AV-202009130122.html https://web.archive.org/web/20200915083726/ This measure was implemented in Bordeaux on September 14. /web/20200915083726/https://www.francebleu.fr/infos/faits-divers-justice/coronavirus-a-bordeaux-les-rassemblements-dans-l-espace-public-limites-a-10-personnes-1600089898
column33: - Access to overseas territories is restricted: all travellers must fill in a travel certificate and carry it at all times during their journey for derogatory travel to certain overseas territories (French Guiana, Mayotte, New Caledonia, French Polynesia, Wallis and Futuna). https://web.archive.org/web/20200916135617/https://www.interieur.gouv.fr/Actualites/L-actu-du-Ministere/Attestation-de-deplacement-et-de-voyage - Metropolitan France: Pr矇fets can re-establish a 100km travel limit in red zones, but this measure has not been implemented so far. https://web.archive.org/web/20200915082826/https://france3-regions.francetvinfo.fr/nouvelle-aquitaine/covid-19-limousin-zone-rouge-se-rapproche-1873104.html
column35: There are no restrictions for travellers coming from the European space, excepted the UK: 2 weeks quarantine required. Tests are mandatory for travellers coming from 'active virus circulation' zones outside the European space. https://web.archive.org/web/20200915083127/https://www.gouvernement.fr/info-coronavirus/vacances
column58: Masks are mandatory in companies, offices, open-spaces since September 1. https://web.archive.org/web/20200915134648/https://www.latribune.fr/economie/france/port-du-masque-obligatoire-les-regles-a-connaitre-dans-l-entreprise-855789.html

column15: Since September 3, classes and schools are closed locally when Covid cases get detected. https://web.archive.org/web/20200915080853/https://www.francebleu.fr/infos/societe/covid-19-deux-premieres-classes-fermees-a-paris-apres-un-cas-de-contamination-1599150031
column42: "On September 3rd, the government announced a new fiscal package to support the recovery of the French economy (Plan de Relance). The plan includes measures amounting to about 100 billion euros over two years and focuses on the ecological transformation of the economy, increasing the competitiveness of French firms, and supporting social and territorial cohesion. About 40 billion of this envelope is expected to be covered by grants from the EU Recovery Fund." https://web.archive.org/web/20201009030538/https://www.imf.org/en/Topics/imf-and-covid19/Policy-Responses-to-COVID-19 Original announcement by PM Castex: https://web.archive.org/web/20201009030648/https://travail-emploi.gouv.fr/actualites/l-actualite-du-ministere/article/france-relance-presentation-du-plan-de-relance

column35: "Entering the French territory is no longer possible from other countries (than the ones listed above) unless for specific imperious reasons and for French citizens or people living in France." https://web.archive.org/web/20200916144252/https://reopen.europa.eu/en/map/FRA

column15: From Tuesday 22 September, 2020, classes are no longer being closed if only one or two pupils has been tested positive. Their classmates and teachers are no longer considered as "contact cases". This measure aims at diminishing the frequency of schools closing /web/20200923080458/https://www.20minutes.fr/sante/2866611-20200921-coronavirus-partir-mardi-protocole-sanitaire-allege-ecoles

column53: The 2021 budget for the national health insurance is 4.2 billion euros higher for COVID-19 tests, vaccines, and additional surgical masks: https://www.lesechos.fr/economie-france/social/tests-vaccins-anti-covid-la-securite-sociale-va-provisionner-4-milliards-pour-2021-1247984

column18: A total closure of bars and restaurants in both the Aix-Marseille region and the French overseas territory of Guadeloupe was announced by Veran as well, starting from Saturday for 14 days. These are the two zones placed on maximum alert. https://web.archive.org/web/20200926094132/https://www.aa.com.tr/en/europe/france-to-roll-out-new-measures-as-covid-19-surges/1983688
column21: In regions on maximum alert then there are no large public gatherings allowed. "In the enhanced alert zones, gatherings are now limited to no more than 10 people, and bars will be compelled to close at 10:00 p.m. starting from Monday. Local and student parties will be prohibited and conference rooms and multi-purpose rooms will also be closed." https://web.archive.org/web/20200926094132/https://www.aa.com.tr/en/europe/france-to-roll-out-new-measures-as-covid-19-surges/1983688
column24: "In the enhanced alert zones, gatherings are limited to no more than 10 people, and bars will be compelled to close at 10:00 p.m. starting from Monday. Local and student parties will be prohibited and conference rooms and multi-purpose rooms will also be closed." https://web.archive.org/web/20200926094132/https://www.aa.com.tr/en/europe/france-to-roll-out-new-measures-as-covid-19-surges/1983688

column18: More departments are in critical alert zones, thus require shut down bars completely: https://web.archive.org/web/20201009023349/https://www.gouvernement.fr/en/coronavirus-covid-19
column21: Although in zones in critical alert, the upper limit for large venues (stadiums, horseracing etc.) is of 1000 people, public gatherings are limited to 10 people, and events such as local f礙tes and student parties are banned. https://web.archive.org/web/20201009023349/https://www.gouvernement.fr/en/coronavirus-covid-19
column24: Gatherings are still limited to 10 people in critical zones https://web.archive.org/web/20201009023349/https://www.gouvernement.fr/en/coronavirus-covid-19
column33: The localisation of COVID responses with different alert zones in different departments is an even stronger recommendation to avoid critical zones.
column38: The Fonds de Solidarite are still in place until the end of 2020. https://web.archive.org/web/20201009030013/https://www.economie.gouv.fr/covid19-soutien-entreprises/entreprises-du-monde-nuit-prolongation-acces-volet-2-fonds-solidarite
column40: Relief from Gas, water, and electricity bills should still be in place according to the govt website https://web.archive.org/web/20201009025457/https://www.economie.gouv.fr/covid19-soutien-entreprises/reponses-gouvernement-difficultes-independants
column49: Still free of charge and without prescriptions even in the hight of a second spike in cases: https://web.archive.org/web/20201009024817/https://www.gouvernement.fr/info-coronavirus/tests-et-depistage

column18: From 6th Oct, bars in Paris closed https://archive.vn/U2Cg8 https://archive.vn/ve2A3#selection-1600.0-1603.19 Bars close in Marseille from 17th Octobre https://archive.vn/e1qK2

Despite this, generally gatherings of more than 10 people are banned. https://archive.vn/ve2A3#selection-1897.0-1915.22
column24: Since 6th Oct, in Paris, no more than 6 people allowed to meet in public spaces, parks and gardens (except for demonstrations, funeral services, professional meetings, testing or food distribution) https://archive.vn/ve2A3#selection-1638.0-1651.84
column33: According to the governments covid 19 website: Within metropolitan France, you may travel freely. You must wear a mask at all times on public transport. https://archive.vn/GmKNQ#selection-367.0-369.79 Cannot find any advice to not travel within France and to avoid certain areas. https://archive.vn/HpAft
column35: According to the US embassys website, US citizens are not allowed to enter France.  Broad restrictions on non-essential travel from many countries outside the European Union, including the United States, remain in place. The French government has defined essential travel as entry by French citizens, residents of France, all foreign (including United States citizen) students (with appropriate visa or residence permit), and spouses and children of French citizens.  In rare cases, the French government will consider allowing travel in humanitarian situations and, reportedly, in cases of business activity important to the French economy. https://archive.vn/ANmaL
column40: According to French government website and IMF website, postponement of rent and utility payments only apply to microenterprises and SMEs. column42: No new measures in this period
column44: No new measures in this period

In response, new priority test centres have been set up, concentrated on four groups: concentrated on four groups; healthcare workers, the elderly or vulnerable, people with symptoms and contact cases - those who have been in close contact with a person who has the virus. https://archive.vn/afu0u
column58: In Marseille and Aix-en-Provence, the wearing of a mask on streets is mandatory. https://archive.vn/Q71Ta Some cities, including Paris, have made face coverings mandatory in all outdoor areas as well. https://archive.vn/ANmaL

column30: Since Saturday 17th October local curfews will be imposed in the Paris region and 8 more cities : Grenoble, Lille, Lyon, Aix-Marseille, Saint-Etienne, Rouen, Montpellier and Toulouse for at least 4 weeks from 9 PM to 6 AM https://archive.vn/GmKNQ#selection-285.81-285.301

column15: France entered a new national lockdown on Friday 30 October. Schools and creches will remain open with social-distancing measures in place, but universities nationwide will be shut with online learning will be carried out. https://web.archive.org/web/20201102183825/https://www.gouvernement.fr/en/coronavirus-covid-19
column18: France entered a new national lockdown on Friday 30 October. People are allowed to leave their home only to go to work (if they cannot work from home). https://web.archive.org/web/20201102182651/https://www.gov.uk/foreign-travel-advice/france/coronavirus
column24: Social gatherings are banned. Everyone found outside has to carry a written statement justifying their journey. 'Places of worship may remain open for weddings (with a maximum of six people) and funerals (with a maximum of 30 people).' https://web.archive.org/web/20201102183825/https://www.gouvernement.fr/en/coronavirus-covid-19
column30: People are allowed to leave their home only to go to work (if they cannot work from home), to buy essential goods, seek medical help or to exercise for one hour a day. Everyone found outside has to carry a written statement justifying their journey. https://web.archive.org/web/20201102183825/https://www.gouvernement.fr/en/coronavirus-covid-19
column33: Travel between different parts of France is not allowed. Internal European borders will remain open but external borders are closed except for essential travel. All travelers arriving in France will be tested at airports and ports. https://web.archive.org/web/20201102183825/https://www.gouvernement.fr/en/coronavirus-covid-19
column35: Travel between different parts of France is not allowed. Internal European borders will remain open but external borders are closed except for essential travel. All travelers arriving in France will be tested at airports and ports. https://web.archive.org/web/20201102183825/https://www.gouvernement.fr/en/coronavirus-covid-19
column42: Announcement that and additional 20 billion Euros will be spent on financial support measures related to the second lockdown, but this will only be spent as part of the end of year budget. So for coding purposes, this needs to wait until the budget has actually been passed. https://archive.vn/DVQjf
column58: There is no national requirement to wear a mask at all times. The decision is up to each department. https://web.archive.org/web/20201109121243/https://www.gouvernement.fr/info-coronavirus (see Questions / reponses, then Pour mon masque) Cloth face coverings are mandatory in indoor settings and on public transportation. Many cities, including Paris, have made face coverings mandatory in all outdoor areas as well. Failure to wear a face covering when required may result in a fine of approximately $150. https://archive.vn/oEa9o#selection-2285.145-2285.413

column38: No change in overall policy, but the government is providing additional targeted partial activity scheme for certain employees of private employers. for the month of November. If the eligibility conditions are met , the system operates as in spring:  Individual employers who wish to use partial activity will have to guarantee at least 80% of their employee's net salary and may not pay an amount lower than the minimum amount provided for in the collective agreement.  They then receive a refund of up to 65% of net scheduled hours. https://archive.vn/lZnMI

column30: In addition to existing policy, Paris bans takeaway food and delivery at night (between 10pm and 6am). https://archive.vn/zQQdC

column18: No change in policy. But one clarification to contrast the restrictions to what was put in place in March: contrary to March, factories and agricultural businesses can continue their activities. Also, in contrast to March, transportation ticket offices, wholesale, food markets and laboratories remain open. https://archive.vn/RxAOE The city of Pariss website lists further businesses that are allowed to remain open: Pharmacies, DIY stores, garages, opticians, IT and phone stores, stationery shops, garden centers, pet stores, dry cleaners, post offices, banks, insurances. https://archive.vn/WcC7K
